<opener><address><addrLine>Telegrams:</addrLine>
<addrLine>"Resources Dublin."</addrLine></address></opener>  Any further communication<lb/>  on this subject should be<lb/>  addressed to<lb/>  "The Secretary,"<lb/>  and the number and the date of<lb/>  this letter should be quoted.<lb/> No.<lb/>  G 1997-16.<lb/> <address>Department of Agriculture<lb/>  and Instruction for Ireland,<lb/>  Dublin,</address> <date>18th May 1916</date>    <salute>Sir,</salute> <p>I have to report,for your information, that<lb/>  from a communication received by the Department from<lb/>  Brigadier General Byrne, Headquarters, Richmond Barracks,<lb/>  it appears that Mr John Shouldice (3, Marino Crescent),<lb/>  a Second Division clerk on the staff of the Statistics<lb/>  and Intelligence Branch of this Department, has been<lb/>  sentenced by Court Martial to five years Penal Servitude<lb/>  for having taken part in the late rebellion. He was,<lb/>  it is stated, among those who surrendered at the Post<lb/>  Office. The Department are communicating with the Lords<lb/>  Commissioners of His Majesty's Treasury and with the<lb/>  Civil Service Commissioners in the case.</p> <p>A further communication will be sent you as<lb/>  soon as possible in the case of some officers of<lb/>  the Department's staff who have not yet returned to duty,<lb/>  when reports from the military authorities have been<lb/>  received.</p> <closer><salute>I am,<lb/>  Sir,<lb/> Your obedient Servant,</salute> M Russell<lb/> Vice President.<lb/> <address><addrLine>The Under Secretary,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Dublin Castle.</addrLine></address></closer>
        
    

    
                </body>
            </text>

        
            
        

         

